solution_text:
By the Chinese Remainder Theorem the specified congruences define a unique class modulo M = 9·25·49·13^2·17^2 = 538,472,025. Solving stepwise (e.g., via Garner’s algorithm) yields an explicit representative a = 452,396,281 (mod M). From the congruences we read off v_3(a−1) = v_5(a−1) = v_7(a−1) = 1 and v_{13}(a+1) = v_{17}(a+1) = 1, with a coprime to all these primes.
For odd p with p | a−1, LTE gives v_p(a^n − 1) = v_p(a−1) + v_p(n) = 1 + v_p(n). For odd p with p | a+1 and n even, LTE gives v_p(a^n − 1) = v_p(a+1) + v_p(n) = 1 + v_p(n). Applying these:
- p=3: 1+v_3(n) = 5 ⇒ v_3(n) = 4;
- p=5: 1+v_5(n) = 4 ⇒ v_5(n) = 3;
- p=7: 1+v_7(n) = 3 ⇒ v_7(n) = 2;
- p=13: n even and 1+v_{13}(n) = 6 ⇒ v_{13}(n) = 5;
- p=17: n even and 1+v_{17}(n) = 5 ⇒ v_{17}(n) = 4.
Hence any solution must be divisible by 2·3^4·5^3·7^2·13^5·17^4. Denote N = 2·3^4·5^3·7^2·13^5·17^4. Then for each listed p we get v_p(a^N − 1) = 1 + v_p(N), which exactly matches the targets 5,4,3,6,5.
Minimality follows since if m omits any required prime power (or is odd), then for some listed p we have v_p(m) < v_p(N) (or parity invalid), forcing v_p(a^m − 1) = 1 + v_p(m) < 1 + v_p(N), so the target at that p fails. Equivalently, using order-lifting (Cohen Thm 1.4.3): ord_p(a) = 1 for p ∈ {3,5,7} and ord_p(a) = 2 for p ∈ {13,17}, with e = v_p(a^{ord_p(a)} − 1) = 1 in all cases. Thus ord_{3^5}(a) = 3^4, ord_{5^4}(a) = 5^3, ord_{7^3}(a) = 7^2, ord_{13^6}(a) = 2·13^5, ord_{17^5}(a) = 2·17^4. Necessarily, these orders divide n to reach the target p-adic depths, giving n divisible by N and showing N is least.
Final answer: N = 2 · 3^4 · 5^3 · 7^2 · 13^5 · 17^4.
